      "text": " Clearly,  $F_K = F_{K,1}$ . A Blaschke selection argument shows that the supremum is actually a maximum; in particular  $b_2(K) < \\infty$  for all  $K \\in \\mathcal{K}^n$ . In fact<sup>[6](#page-9-1)</sup>,  $b_2(K) \\leq 2$  for any K. Notice that  $b_2(K) > 1$  is equivalent to not having  $F_K \\geq 0$  (i.e. to existence of a pair  $(A, B)$  such that  $F_K(A, B) < 0$ ).",
