      "order": "6",
      "anno_id": 1,
      "text": " If a property  $\\mathcal{P}$  (for instance, being decomposable) is such that when  $K$  has  $\\mathcal{P}$ , then  $F_K$  cannot be non-negative (on all of  $(\\mathcal{K}^n)^2$ ), we shall say that  $\\mathcal{P}$  is an excluding condition (in the terminology of [\\[SZ16\\]](#page-9-1), a convex body  $K$  cannot both satisfy  $\\mathcal{P}$  and satisfy *Bezout inequalities*). It was shown in [\\[SSZ1, SSZ2\\]](#page-9-1) that being weakly decomposable (a property which in particular includes being a polytope other than an  $n$ -simplex, or being decomposable) is an excluding condition. Denote  $\\mathcal{K}_F$  the subclass of  $\\mathcal{K}^n$  consisting of convex bodies having at least one facet :  $\\mathcal{K}_F$  is closed under Minkowski addition, and contains the class of  $n$ -polytopes. In this section we give a new excluding condition, which concerns bodies  $K \\in \\mathcal{K}_F$ . We will work in  $\\mathbb{R}^n$  with  $n \\geq 3$.",
